<chapter xml:id="chapter-proof-methods" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Definitions and proof methods</title>

<section xml:id="section-proof-methods-defs">
<title>Definitions</title>

<p>
Definitions are used in mathematics to label objects that have special properties, and to group all such objects together.
Be careful with definitions: as stated by mathematicians, they often contain implicit conditions.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-proof-methods-define-prime">
	<p>
	A number is called
	<term>prime</term><idx>prime number</idx>
	if its only divisors are <m>1</m> and itself.
	</p>
	<p> This definition has some hidden parts: a more complete definition would be as follows. </p>
	<p>
	A number is called <term>prime</term> if
	<ol marker="(i)">
		<li> it is an integer, </li>
		<li> it is strictly greater than <m>1</m>, and </li>
		<li> there does not exist any <em>other</em> number greater than <m>1</m> which divides it. </li>
	</ol>
	</p>
</example>

<p>
You should view a definition as a <em>technical test</em> or <em>collection of technical tests</em> that an object must pass before it can be given a specific label.
</p>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement><p>
		Demonstrate that, according to the technical definition of <term>prime</term>,
		<m>17</m> is prime but <m>21</m> is not.
	</p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Let us test <m>17</m>.
		<ol marker="(i)">
			<li> Yes, <m>17</m> is an integer. </li>
			<li> Yes, <m>17 \gt 1</m>. </li>
			<li>
				None of the numbers in the following list is an integer:
				<me>
					\frac{17}{2}, \frac{17}{3}, \frac{17}{4},
					\dotsc,
					\frac{17}{16}, \frac{17}{18}, \frac{17}{19},
					\dotsc
				</me>.
			</li>
		</ol>
		So <m>17</m> is prime since it passes the technical tests that define the concept of <term>prime</term>.
		</p><p>
		Now let us test <m>21</m>.
		<ol marker="(i)">
			<li> Yes, <m>21</m> is an integer. </li>
			<li> Yes, <m>21 \gt 1</m>. </li>
			<li> However, clearly <m>21/3 = 7</m> is an integer, so <m>3</m> divides <m>21</m>. </li>
		</ol>
		So <m>21</m> is not prime, since it fails <em>at least one</em> of the technical tests that define the concept of <term>prime</term>.
		</p>
	</solution>
</problem>

<p> Often, the first thing we do in mathematics is to look for ways to make testing our definition easier. </p>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-proof-methods-prime-refine"><p>
	Suppose <m>n</m> is an integer with <m>n \ge 2</m>.
	Then <m>n</m> is prime if and only if <m>n/m</m> is <em>not</em> an integer for every integer <m>m</m> with <m>2 \le m \lt \frac{n}{2}</m>.
</p></proposition>

<p>
The proof is left to you as
<xref ref="exercise-proof-methods-prime-def-1" />.
</p>

<aside><title>See also</title><p>
	<xref ref="exercise-proof-methods-prime-def-2" />
	for a refinement of the statement of <xref ref="proposition-proof-methods-prime-refine" />.
</p></aside>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement><p> Demonstrate that <m>17</m> is prime. </p></statement>
	<solution><title>(Sketch)</title><p>
		By the proposition, to check that <m>17</m> is prime we now only need to note that none of the numbers in the following shorter list is an integer:
		<me>
			\frac{17}{2}, \frac{17}{3}, \frac{17}{4},
			\dotsc
			\frac{17}{8}
		</me>.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-proof-methods-math-statements">
<title>Common mathematical statements</title>

<p>
In mathematics, we often want to prove that some statement <m>P</m>
<term><xref ref="definition-symb-lang-logically-implies" text="title"/></term>
some other statement <m>Q</m>;
<ie /> we want to prove that <m>P \lgcimplies Q</m> or <m>(\forall x)(P(x) \lgcimplies Q(x))</m>.
Note that the universal form covers the common statement <q>all <m>A</m> are <m>B</m></q>, since this can be rephrased <q>for all <m>x</m>, if <m>x</m> is <m>A</m> then <m>x</m> is <m>B</m></q>.
</p><p>
Below are some common methods for proving <m>P \lgcimplies Q</m>.
In the universal case <m>(\forall x)(P(x) \lgcimplies Q(x))</m>, the domain of <m>x</m> may be infinite, so we cannot prove <m>P(x) \lgcimplies Q(x)</m> for each specific <m>x</m>, one-by-one.
Instead, we treat <m>x</m> as a <em>fixed but arbitrary</em> object in the domain, and try to construct an argument proving <m>P(x) \lgcimplies Q(x)</m> which does not depending on knowing the specific object <m>x</m>.
So all of the methods below can also be used in the universal case.
</p><p>
Since a conditional <m>P \lgccond Q</m> is true automatically when <m>P</m> is false, it will be a tautology as long as we cannot have the case of <m>P</m> true and <m>Q</m> false at the same time.
(See <xref ref="figure-symb-lang-connectives-truth-tables" />.)
Therefore, we (almost always) <alert>begin a proof by assuming that <m>P</m> is true</alert>, and proceed to <alert>demonstrate that <m>Q</m> must then also be true</alert>, based on that assumption.
</p>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-proof-methods-direct">
<!-- \zlabel{SECTION::proof.methods::direct.proof} -->
<title>Direct proof</title>

<paragraphs><title>Recall</title><p>
	The argument
	<me>
		A \lgccond C_1, C_1 \lgccond C_2, \dotsc, C_{m-1} \lgccond C_m, C_m \lgccond B
		\therefore A \lgccond B
	</me>
	is valid
	(<xref ref="definition-arg-extended-law-of-syllogism" text="title" />).
</p></paragraphs>

<identity><title>Direct proof</title>
	<idx>direct proof</idx>
	<idx><h>proof</h><h>direct</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Procedure</h><h>direct proof</h></idx>
	<p><ul>
		<li>
			To prove <m>P \lgcimplies Q</m>, start by assuming that <m>P</m> is true.
			Then, through a sequence of (appropriately justified) intermediate conclusions,
			arrive at <m>Q</m> as a final conclusion.
		</li>
		<li>
			To prove <m>(\forall x)\bbrac{P(x) \lgcimplies Q(x)}</m>, start by assuming that <m>x</m> is an <em>arbitrary but unspecified</em> element in the domain such that <m>P(x)</m> is true.
			The first sentence in your argument should be:
			<q>Suppose <m>x</m> is a <fillin characters="5" /> such that <m>P(x)</m></q>,
			where the blank is filled in by the definition of the domain of <m>x</m>.
			Then,
			through a sequence of (appropriately justified) intermediate conclusions that do not depend on knowing the specific object <m>x</m> in the domain,
			arrive at <m>Q(x)</m> as a conclusion.
		</li>
	</ul></p>
</identity>

<problem xml:id="wexample-proof-methods-n-even-n-sq-even"> <!-- worked example -->
	<!-- \label{WEXAMPLE::n.even.n.sq.even} -->
	<statement><p> <em>Prove:</em> If <m>n</m> is even, then <m>n^2</m> even. </p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		Let <m>P(n)</m> represent the predicate <q><m>n</m> is even</q> and let <m>Q(n)</m> represent the predicate <q><m>n^2</m> is even</q>,
		with domain the integers.
		</p><p>
		Suppose that <m>n</m> is an arbitrary (but unspecified) integer such that <m>n</m> is even.
		Then there exists an integer <m>m</m> such that <m>n = 2m</m>, and so <m>n^2 = 4m^2 = 2(2m)</m> is even.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<paragraphs><title>Check your understanding</title><p>
	Attempt
	<xref first="exercise-proof-methods-direct-1" last="exercise-proof-methods-direct-3">Exercises</xref>.
</p></paragraphs>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-proof-methods-cases">
<title>Reduction to cases</title>

<fact xml:id="fact-proof-methods-distrib-cond-disj">
	<statement><p>
		The following logical equivalence holds:
		<me>
			(s_1 \lgcor s_2 \lgcor \dotsb \lgcor s_m) \lgccond t
			\; \lgcequiv \;
			(s_1 \lgccond t) \lgcand (s_2 \lgccond t) \lgcand \dotsb \lgcand (s_m \lgccond t)
		</me>.
	</p></statement>
	<proof><title>Proof idea</title><p>
		This is just an extended version of
		<xref ref="example-logic-equiv-conditional-demorgan" />.
	</p></proof>
</fact>

<p>
If <me> C_1 \lgcor C_2 \lgcor \dotsb \lgcor C_m </me> is a tautology, then
<me>
	P
	\; \lgcequiv \;
	P \lgcand (C_1 \lgcor \dotsb \lgcor C_m)
	\; \lgcequiv \;
	(P \lgcand C_1) \lgcor \dotsb \lgcor (P \lgcand C_m)
</me>.
By substitution and <xref ref="fact-proof-methods-distrib-cond-disj" />,
<me>
	P \lgccond Q \; \lgcequiv \;
	(P \lgcand C_1 \lgccond Q) \lgcand \dotsb \lgcand (P \lgcand C_m \lgccond Q).
</me>
A conjunction is only true if each <q>factor</q> in the conjunction is true,
so the conjunction on the right above can only be a tautology if each conditional <m>P \lgcand C_1 \lgccond Q</m> is a tautology.
Therefore, when we have a collection of statements <m>C_1,\dotsc,C_m</m> so that
<me> C_1 \lgcor C_2 \lgcor \dotsb \lgcor C_m </me>
is a tautology,
we can prove <m> P \lgccond Q </m> by instead proving each of <m>P \lgcand C_i \lgcimplies Q</m> one at a time.
This is also valid for universal statements, since <m>\forall</m> distributes over <m>\lgcand</m>
(<xref ref="proposition-pred-logic-distrib-quants" />).
</p><p>
Now, having to prove many slightly more complicated statements <m>P \lgcand C_i \lgcimplies Q</m> seems like a lot more work than just proving the single simple statement <m>P \lgccond Q</m> <mdash />
why would we want to go to all this extra effort?
</p>

<hypothesis><statement><p> <!-- idea -->
	Each case statement <m>C_i</m> provides extra information that can be combined with the assumption that <m>P</m> is true to arrive at the conclusion that <m>Q</m> must also be true.
</p></statement></hypothesis>

<identity><title>Reduction to cases</title> <!-- Procedure -->
	<idx>reduction to cases</idx>
	<idx><h>proof</h><h>by reduction to cases</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Procedure</h><h>reduction to cases</h></idx>
	<p><ul>
		<li>
			To prove <m>P\lgcimplies Q</m>,
			determine a set of cases <m>C_1, C_2, \dotsc, C_m</m> such that <m>C_1 \lgcor C_2 \lgcor \dotsb \lgcor C_m</m> is true,
			then provide a separate proof of each logical implication <m>P \lgcand C_i \lgcimplies Q</m>.
		</li>
		<li>
			To prove <m>(\forall x)\bbrac{P(x)\lgcimplies Q(x)}</m>,
			determine a set of cases <m>C_1(x), C_2(x), \dotsc, C_m(x)</m> such that
			<me> (\forall x) \bbrac{C_1(x) \lgcor C_2(x) \lgcor \dotsb \lgcor C_m(x)} </me>
			is true, then provide a separate proof of each universally quantified logical implication <m>(\forall x)\bbrac{P(x) \lgcand C_i(x) \lgcimplies Q(x)}</m>.
		</li>
	</ul></p>
</identity>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement><p> Show <m>n^2 - n</m> is always even. </p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		Let <m>P(n)</m> represent the predicate <q><m>n</m> is an integer</q> and let <m>Q(n)</m> represent the predicate <q><m>n^2 - n</m> is even</q>, each with domain the integers. Note that <m>P(n)</m> is actually true for each <m>n</m> in the domain,
		since our original statement makes no extra premise on <m>n</m> besides its domain.
		</p><p>
		Suppose that <m>n</m> is an integer.
		Break into cases based on whether <m>n</m> is even or odd; in each case, proceed by direct proof.
		</p>
		<case><title>Case <m>n</m> even</title><p>
			If <m>n</m> is even, then there exists an integer <m>m</m> such that <m>n = 2m</m>.
			Then, <me> n^2 - n = n(n-1) = 2m(2m - 1) </me> is also even.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Case <m>n</m> odd</title><p>
			If <m>n</m> is odd, then <m>n - 1</m> is even, so there exists an integer <m>m</m> such that <m>n - 1 = 2m</m>, or <m>n = 2m + 1</m>.
			Then, <me> n^2 - n = n(n-1) = (2m+1)(2m) </me> is even.
		</p></case>
	</solution>
</problem>

<warning><p> Make sure your cases cover all possibilities! (Though it is not necessary that your cases by non-overlapping.) </p></warning>

<paragraphs><title>Check your understanding</title><p>
	Attempt <xref ref="exercise-proof-methods-cases" />.
</p></paragraphs>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-proof-methods-disj">
<title>Statements involving disjunction</title>

<p>
First, let's consider a conditional statement with a disjunction on the hypothesis side.
To prove a statement of the form <m>(P_1 \lgcor P_2) \lgcimplies Q</m>,
we can use <xref ref="fact-proof-methods-distrib-cond-disj" /> to decompose into two conditionals:
<me> (P_1 \lgcor P_2) \lgccond Q \lgcequiv (P_1 \lgccond Q) \lgcand (P_2 \lgccond Q) </me>.
Appealing to the properties of conjunction, as in our discussion of reduction to cases,
we see that we can prove <m>P_1 \lgcimplies Q</m> and <m>P_2 \lgcimplies Q</m> by separate proofs.
</p>

<p>
What about a conditional with a disjunction on the conclusion side?
To prove a statement of the form <m>P \lgcimplies (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2)</m>, we can again reduce to cases, but in a sort of tricky way.
For any statement, there are only two possibilities <mdash /> either the statement is true or it is false.
(See <xref ref="example-symb-lang-basic-tauts-law-excl-mid">Basic Tautology</xref>
in <xref ref="example-symb-lang-basic-tauts" />.
Apply this fact to one of the statements we are trying to prove.
</p>

<!-- %Applying this fact to one of our desired conclusions, say <m>Q_1</m>, leads to two separate cases: regardless of <m>P</m>, exactly one of the two cases <m>Q_1=\true</m>, <m>Q_1=\false</m>, is true.
%Recall that <m>C \lgcor \lgcnot C</m> is a tautology, so we can use this in a reduction to cases:
%<me>
%	P \lgccond (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2)
%	\lgcequiv \bigl[(P \lgcand C) \lgccond (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2) \bigr]
%		\lgcand \bigl[(P \lgcand \lgcnot C) \lgccond (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2) \bigr].
%</me>
%Let's see what happens when we substitute <m>C = Q_1</m> into the above equivalence:
%<me>
%	P \lgccond (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2)
%	\lgcequiv \bigl[(P \lgcand Q_1) \lgccond (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2) \bigr]
%		\lgcand \bigl[(P \lgcand \lgcnot Q_1) \lgccond (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2) \bigr].
%</me>
%Now, <m>(P \lgcand Q_1) \lgccond (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2)</m> is a tautology. \begin{inlinenote}[See]Exercise \ref{EXERCISE::disjunctive tautology} of \S\zref{CHAPTER::symb.lang}.\end{inlinenote} Therefore,
%<md><mrow>
%	P \lgccond (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2)
%	&\lgcequiv \bigl[(P \lgcand Q_1) \lgccond (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2) \bigr]
%		\lgcand \bigl[(P \lgcand \lgcnot Q_1) \lgccond (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2) \bigr]
%	\\
%	&\lgcequiv (P \lgcand \lgcnot Q_1) \lgccond (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2)
%	\\
%	&\lgcequiv (P \lgcand \lgcnot Q_1) \lgccond Q_2.
%</mrow></md>
%\begin{inlinenote}[See]Exercise \ref{EXERCISE::equiv.neg.wedge.vee} of \S\zref{CHAPTER::logic.equiv} for the last equivalence.\end{inlinenote} -->

<identity xml:id="procedure-proof-methods-prove-disjunction">
	<!-- \label{PROC::prove.disjunction} -->
	<title>Proof of conditional involving disjunction</title>
	<idx><h>proof</h><h>of conditional involving disjunction</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Procedure</h><h>proof of conditional involving disjunction</h></idx>
	<p>
	To prove a statement of the form <m>P \lgcimplies (Q_1 \lgcor Q_2)</m>, start by assuming that <m>P</m> is true and <m>Q_1</m> is <alert>false</alert>.
	Try to show that these assumptions lead to <m>Q_2</m> being true.
	</p>
</identity>

<hypothesis><statement><p> <!-- idea -->
	There are only two possibilities for <m>Q_1</m>: either it is true or it is false.
	If <m>Q_1</m> is true, then <m>Q_1 \lgcor Q_2</m> is already true, regardless of the truth values of <m>P</m> and <m>Q_2</m>, so there is nothing to prove in this case.
	On the other hand, if <m>Q_1</m> is false, the only way <m>Q_1 \lgcor Q_2</m> could be true is if <m>Q_2</m> is true.
</p></statement></hypothesis>

<note><p><ul>
	<li>
		Also see
		<xref ref="exercise-logic-equiv-neg-and-or" />.
	</li>
	<li>
	Of course, you can swap the roles of <m>Q_1</m> and <m>Q_2</m> above:
	you could also start by assuming that <m>P</m> is true and <m>Q_2</m> is false, then try to show that this leads to <m>Q_1</m> being true.
	</li>
	<li>
		Another strategy is to attempt a <term>proof by contradiction</term>
		(discussed in <xref ref="section-proof-methods-contradiction" /> below).
		By DeMorgan, <m>\lgcnot(Q_1 \lgcor Q_2) \lgcequiv \lgcnot Q_1 \lgcand \lgcnot Q_2</m>, so for this strategy, you should start by assuming that <m>P</m> is true and <em>both</em> <m>Q_1</m> and <m>Q_2</m> are false.
		Then, try to arrive at a contradiction.
	</li>
</ul></p></note>

<problem xml:id="wexample-proof-methods-every-odd-1-or-3-mod-4"> <!-- worked example -->
	<!-- \label{WEXAMPLE::every.odd.1.or.3.mod.4} -->
	<statement><p> <em>Prove:</em> Every odd number is either <m>1</m> more or <m>3</m> more than a multiple of <m>4</m>. </p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		Let <m>P(n)</m> represent the predicate <q><m>n</m> is odd</q>, let <m>Q_1(n)</m> represent the predicate <q><m>n</m> is <m>1</m> more than a multiple of <m>4</m></q>, and let <m>Q_2(n)</m> represent the predicate <q><m>n</m> is <m>3</m> more than a multiple of <m>4</m></q>, each with domain the integers.
		</p><p>
		Start by assuming that <m>n</m> is an odd number that is <em>not</em> <m>1</m> more than a multiple of <m>4</m>.
		We must now try to show that <m>n</m> <em>is</em> <m>3</m> more than a multiple of <m>4</m>.
		We know that <m>n</m> is odd, so there exists a number <m>m</m> such that <m>n = 2m + 1</m>.
		However, since <m>n</m> is <em>not</em> <m>1</m> more than a multiple of <m>4</m>, <m>2m</m> cannot be a multiple of <m>4</m>, and so <m>m</m> cannot be a multiple of <m>2</m>.
		Therefore, <m>m</m> is also odd, and so there exists another number <m>\ell</m> such that <m>m = 2\ell + 1</m>.
		Then
		<me> n = 2m + 1 = 2(2\ell + 1) + 1 = 4\ell + 3 </me>,
		which says that <m>n</m> is <m>3</m> more than a multiple of <m>4</m>, as desired.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-proof-methods-contrapos">
<title>Proving the contrapositive</title>

<paragraphs><title>Recall</title><p>
	<term><xref ref="theorem-logic-equiv-modus-tollens" text="title" /></term>:
	<m>P \lgccond Q \lgcequiv \lgcnot Q \lgccond \lgcnot P</m>.
</p></paragraphs>

<identity><title>Proof by proving the contrapositive</title> <!-- procedure -->
	<idx><h>proof</h><h>by proving the contrapositive</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Procedure</h><h>proof by proving the contrapositive</h></idx>
	<p> To prove <m>P \lgcimplies Q</m>, you can instead prove <m>\lgcnot Q \lgcimplies \lgcnot P</m>. </p>
</identity>

<example><p>
	In <xref ref="wexample-proof-methods-n-even-n-sq-even" />,
	we proved that the square of an even number is also even.
	Therefore, this also constitutes a proof of the contrapositive statement:
	if the square of a number is odd, then that number is also odd.
</p></example>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement><p> Prove that every prime number larger than <m>2</m> is odd. </p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		We want to prove the following universally quantified conditional
		(<q>for all <m>p</m></q> omitted, domain is positive integers).
		<dl>
			<li><title>conditional</title><p> if (<m>p</m> is prime and <m>p>2</m>) then <m>p</m> is odd. </p></li>
			<li><title>contrapositive</title><p> if <m>p</m> is not odd, then not (<m>p</m> is prime and <m>p>2</m>) </p></li>
			<li><title>DeMorgan substitution</title><p> if <m>p</m> is not odd, then (<m>p</m> is not prime or <m>p \le 2</m>) </p></li>
		</dl>
		These are all equivalent.
		</p><p>
		Let's prove the last statement: as in the procedure for proving conditionals with a disjunction, start by assuming that <m>p</m> is not odd and <m>p \gt 2</m>.
		We must then show that <m>p</m> is not prime.
		Since <m>p</m> is not odd, it is divisible by <m>2</m>.
		But since <m>p \gt 2</m>, <m>p</m> is divisible by a number <em>other than</em> <m>1</m> and <m>p</m> itself.
		Therefore, <m>p</m> is not prime.
		</p>
	</solution>
</problem>

<paragraphs><title>Check your understanding</title><p>
	Attempt <xref ref="exercise-proof-methods-contrapos" />.
</p></paragraphs>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-proof-methods-counterexample">
<title>Proof by counterexample</title>

<p> Sometimes we want to prove that <m>P \not\lgcimplies Q</m>; <ie /> that <m>P \lgccond Q</m> is <em>not</em> a tautology. </p>

<paragraphs><title>Recall</title><p>
	The equivalence
	<me> P \lgccond Q \lgcequiv (P \lgcand C_1 \lgccond Q) \lgcand \dotsb \lgcand (P \lgcand C_m \lgccond Q) </me>
	holds for any set of cases <m>C_1, C_2, \dotsc, C_m</m> such that <m>C_1 \lgcor \dotsb \lgcor C_m</m> is a tautology.
	(See <xref ref="section-proof-methods-cases" />.)
</p></paragraphs>

<p>
So if <m>P \lgcand C_i \lgccond Q</m> is <em>not</em> a tautology for at least one <m>i</m>,
then <m>P \lgccond Q</m> also cannot be a tautology.
Again, this also works in the universal case since <m>\forall</m> distributes over <m>\lgcand</m>
(<xref ref="proposition-pred-logic-distrib-quants" />).
</p>

<p><dl><li>
	<title>counterexample</title>
	<idx>counterexample</idx>
	<p>
	relative to the logical implication <m>P \lgcimplies Q</m>,
	a statement <m>C</m> such that <m>P \lgcand C \lgccond Q</m> is false
	</p>
</li></dl></p>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement>
		<p>
		In <xref ref="exercise-proof-methods-contrapos" />,
		you are asked to prove the following statement by proving the contrapositive.
		</p>
		<blockquote><p> If <m>2^n - 1</m> prime, then <m>n</m> is prime. </p></blockquote>
		<p> Prove that the <em>converse</em> of this statement is <em>false</em>. </p>
	</statement>
	<solution><p>
		The converse statement is <q>If <m>n</m> is prime, then <m>2^n - 1</m> is prime.</q>
		But the case <m>n=11</m> is a <term>counterexample</term>:
		<me> 2^{11} - 1 = 2047 = 23 \cdot 89 </me> is not prime even though <m>n = 11</m> is prime.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<paragraphs><title>Check your understanding</title><p>
	Attempt <xref ref="exercise-proof-methods-counterexample" />.
</p></paragraphs>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-proof-methods-biconditionals">
<title>Proving biconditionals</title>

<p>
We also often want to prove that two statements <m>P,Q</m> are equivalent;
<ie /> that <m>P \lgcequiv Q</m>.
</p>

<fact>
	<statement><p>
		The equivalence
		<me> P \lgcbicond Q \; \lgcequiv \; (P \lgccond Q) \lgcand (Q \lgccond P) </me>
		holds;
		<ie /> a biconditional is equivalent to the conjunction of the corresponding conditional <m>P\lgccond Q</m> <em>and</em> its converse.
	</p></statement>
	<proof><p>
		You are asked to prove this by truth table in
		<xref ref="exercise-logic-equiv-biconditional-constructed" />.
	</p></proof>
</fact>

<identity><title>Proving a biconditional</title> <!-- procedure -->
	<idx><h>proof</h><h>of a biconditional</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Procedure</h><h>proving a biconditional</h></idx>
	<p> To prove <m>P \lgcequiv Q</m>, prove <m>P \lgcimplies Q</m> and <m>Q \lgcimplies P</m> separately. </p>
</identity>

<p>
As usual, this also works in the universal case since <m>\forall</m> distributes over <m>\lgcand</m>
(<xref ref="proposition-pred-logic-distrib-quants" />).
</p>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement><p> <em>Prove:</em> A number is even if and only if its square is even. </p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		We want to prove that the following quantified biconditional
		(<q>for all <m>n</m></q> omitted, domain is nonnegative, whole numbers).
		<dl>
			<li><title>biconditional</title><p> <m>n</m> is even if and only if <m>n^2</m> is even. </p></li>
			<li><title>conditional and converse</title><p> (if <m>n</m> is even then <m>n^2</m> is even) and (if <m>n^2</m> is even then <m>n</m> is even) </p></li>
			<li><title>contrapositive and converse</title><p> (if <m>n^2</m> is odd then <m>n</m> is odd) and (if <m>n^2</m> is even then <m>n</m> is even) </p></li>
			<li><title>conditional and inverse</title><p> (if <m>n</m> is even then <m>n^2</m> is even) and (if <m>n</m> is odd then <m>n^2</m> is odd) </p></li>
		</dl>
		These are all equivalent, so we could prove any one pair.
		</p>
		<case><title>Original conditional</title><p> This is proved as <xref ref="wexample-proof-methods-n-even-n-sq-even" />. </p></case>
		<case><title>Converse</title><p>
			If <m>n^2</m> is even, then there exists an integer <m>m</m> such that <m>n^2 = 2m</m>, so that <m>n = \sqrt{2m}</m> <ellipsis /> ?
			We seem to be stuck.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Inverse</title><p>
			If <m>n</m> is odd, then there exists an integer <m>m</m> such that <m>n = 2m+1</m>.
			Then, <m>n^2 = 4m^2 + 4m + 1</m> is odd.
		</p></case>
	</solution>
</problem>

<exercise><p> Attempt <xref ref="exercise-proof-methds-bicond" />. </p></exercise>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-proof-methods-contradiction">
<!-- \zlabel{SECTION::proof.methods::proof.by.contradiction} -->
<title>Proof by contradiction</title>

<fact>
	<statement><p>
		For any logically false statement <m>e</m>,
		we have
		<me> s \lgccond t \; \lgcequiv \; (s \lgcand \lgcnot t) \lgccond e </me>.
	</p></statement>
	<proof><p>
		First, <m>s\lgccond t</m> is false precisely when <m>s</m> is true and <m>t</m> is false.
		On the other hand,
		<m>(s \lgcand \lgcnot t) \lgccond e</m> is false precisely when <m>s \lgcand \lgcnot t</m> is true,
		and <m>s \lgcand \lgcnot t</m> is true precisely when <m>s, \lgcnot t</m> are both true, <ie /> when <m>s</m> is true and <m>t</m> is false.
	</p></proof>
</fact>

<identity> <!-- procedure -->
	<title>Proof by contradiction</title>
	<idx><h>proof</h><h>by contradiction</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Procedure</h><h>proof by contradiction</h></idx>
	<p><ul>
		<li> To prove <m>P \lgcimplies Q</m>, devise a false statement <m>E</m> such that <m>(P \lgcand \lgcnot Q) \lgcimplies E</m>. </li>
		<li>
			To prove <m>(\forall x)\bbrac{P(x) \lgcimplies Q(x)}</m>, devise a predicate <m>E(x)</m> such that <m>(\forall x)\bbrac{\lgcnot E(x)}</m> is true
			(<ie /> <m>E(x)</m> is false for <em>all</em> <m>x</m> in the domain),
			but <m>(\forall x)\bigl[\bbrac{P(x) \lgcand \lgcnot Q(x)} \lgcimplies E(x)\bigr]</m>.
		</li>
	</ul></p>
</identity>

<note><p>
	Usually <m>E</m> is taken to be some variation of <m>C \lgcand \lgcnot C</m>, for some statement <m>C</m>.
	(See the <term>Law of Contradiction</term>, recorded as
	<xref ref="example-symb-lang-basic-tauts-law-contra">Basic Tautology</xref>
	in <xref ref="example-symb-lang-basic-tauts" />.)
</p></note>

<!-- <warning><p>
	In set theory, it is possible to violate the Law of Contradiction (see the warning on page \pageref{WARNING::vac.true.contra}), so some care must be exercised when choosing <m>C</m> to use in <m>E = C \lgcand \lgcnot C</m>.
</p></warning> -->

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<!-- \label{WEXAMPLE::sq.rt.2.irrational} -->
	<statement><p> Prove that <m>\sqrt{2}</m> is irrational. </p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		We want to prove the quantified conditional with domain the real numbers:
		for all <m>x</m>, if <m>x^2 = 2</m> and <m>x \gt 0</m> then <m>x</m> is not rational.
		</p><p>
		Suppose that <m>x</m> is a real number such that <m>x^2 = 2</m> and <m>x \gt 0</m>.
		By contradiction, also assume that <m>x</m> <em>is</em> rational.
		We want this extra assumption to lead to a false statement.
		Now, <m>x</m> rational means <m>x = a/b</m> for some integers <m>a,b</m>.
		We may assume <m>a,b</m> are both positive, since <m>x \gt 0</m>.
		We may also assume <m>a,b</m> have no common factors (<ie /> fraction <m>a/b</m> is in lowest terms).
		Then,
		<md>
			<mrow> x^2 = 2 \amp \; \lgcimplies \; a^2 = 2 b^2, </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \; \lgcimplies \; a^2 \text{ even}, </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \; \lgcimplies \; a \text{ even}, </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \; \lgcimplies \; a = 2m, \text{ some } m, </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \; \lgcimplies \; 2 b^2 = a^2 = 4m^2, </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \; \lgcimplies \; b^2 = 2m^2, </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \; \lgcimplies \; b^2 \text{ even}, </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \; \lgcimplies \; b \text{ even}. </mrow>
		</md>
		But if both <m>a,b</m> are even, then <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are both divisible by <m>2</m>.
		We have arrived at our contradiction: <m>a,b</m> have no common factor but <m>a,b</m> have a common factor of <m>2</m>.
		That is, we have shown the following.
		</p>
		<blockquote><p>
			For all <m>x</m>,
			if <m> \bbrac{ (x^2 = 2 \text{ and } x \gt 0) \text{ and } x \text{ not irrational}} </m>
			then (there exist positive integers <m>a,b</m> such that <m>x = a/b</m> and <m>a,b</m> have no common divisor and <m>a,b</m> have a common divisor).
		</p></blockquote>
	</solution>
</problem>

<exercise><p>
	Attempt
	<xref first="exercise-proof-methods-contradiction-1" last="exercise-proof-methods-contradiction-3">Exercises</xref>.
</p></exercise>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-proof-methods-exist-unique">
<title>Existence and uniqueness</title>

<p>
In mathematics we often want to know whether an object with specific desirable properties actually exists.
In symbolic language, this is just <m>(\exists x)A(x)</m>.
Conceptually, this is easy to do: just find an example!
(In practice, this can often be quite difficult.)
</p>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement><p> Prove that <m>851</m> is not prime. </p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		We want to prove the quantified statement
		<me> (\exists n)\bbrac{ (n \ne 1) \lgcand (n \ne 851) \lgcand (n \text{ divides } 851)} </me>,
		with domain the positive, whole numbers.
		Testing each number, one by one, starting at <m>n = 2</m>, we find that using <m>n=23</m> fits the bill.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<p>
Once we have found an example for an existential statement, we also often want to know whether there are more examples, or whether the one we have found is <term>unique</term>.
Suppose <m>x_0</m> is our concrete example proving <m>(\exists x)A(x)</m>.
To show that <m>x_0</m> is unique, we should prove the universal statement: <m>(\forall y)\bbrac{ A(y) \lgccond (y = x_0) }</m>.
This translates as the following.
</p>
<blockquote><p> For all <m>y</m>, if <m>A(y)</m> is true, then <m>y=x_0</m>. </p></blockquote>
<p> That is, the only way object <m>y</m> can satisfy <m>A(y)</m> is if <m>y</m> is actually our original example <m>x_0</m>. </p>

<identity xml:id="procedure-proof-methods-proving-unique">
	<title>Proving uniqueness</title>
	<idx><h>proof</h><h>of uniqueness</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Procedure</h><h>proving uniqueness</h></idx>
	<p>
	To prove that <m>x = x_0</m> is the unique instance of an object <m>x</m> such that <m>A(x)</m> is true,
	assume that <m>y</m> is also an object such that <m>A(y)</m> is true, and prove that <m>y = x_0</m>.
	</p>
</identity>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement><p> Prove that <m>2</m> is the unique positive number that is both prime and even. </p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Suppose <m>n</m> is a positive number which is both prime and even.
		Since <m>n</m> is even, it is divisible by <m>2</m>.
		But since <m>n</m> is prime, it is divisble by <em>only</em> <m>1</m> and itself.
		Therefore, <m>2</m> and <q>itself</q> must be the same, <ie /> <m>n = 2</m>.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

</section>

